If you have a technical problem, please share your issue in the chat during the meeting.

40
00:04:46,949 --> 00:04:54,591
And now, after all of that, I would like to introduce Justin Antos from the MBTA.

41
00:04:54,651 --> 00:04:59,412
He is the Senior Director of Bus Transformation, and he will give some opening remarks.

42
00:04:59,792 --> 00:05:00,192
Justin?

43
00:05:04,953 --> 00:05:05,453
Thanks, Regan.

44
00:05:06,132 --> 00:05:06,613
Good evening.

45
00:05:07,033 --> 00:05:09,154
As Reagan said, my name is Justin Antos.

46
00:05:09,674 --> 00:05:16,819
I'm the director of bus transformation here at the T. I'm excited to be here tonight to kick off this meeting for our bus network redesign.

47
00:05:17,299 --> 00:05:18,100
Why am I excited?

48
00:05:19,501 --> 00:05:27,846
Because transit is essential to the region's economy, especially post-pandemic, and MBTA buses serve our most transit-dependent population.

49
00:05:29,207 --> 00:05:34,490
Bus ridership at the MBTA was the most resilient during COVID, stronger even today,

50
00:05:35,145 --> 00:05:36,186
than many rail services.

51
00:05:37,867 --> 00:05:47,214
But our region has changed significantly over the past few years and decades, and our bus network needs to rise to the challenge and change with it.

52
00:05:47,974 --> 00:05:53,218
It's essential that the T's bus network adapts to how, where, and when people travel today.

53
00:05:54,839 --> 00:06:03,125
Back in May, we released a draft map, a proposal for service, and all last summer, and including this fall,

54
00:06:03,737 --> 00:06:07,360
we've received over 20,000 public comments on it.

55
00:06:08,120 --> 00:06:10,002
We've reviewed all of those comments.

56
00:06:10,242 --> 00:06:11,102
We've read them all.

57
00:06:11,763 --> 00:06:23,491
And we've had dozens of meetings with cities, municipalities, residents, elected officials, neighborhood groups, many, many meetings over the past few months.

58
00:06:25,012 --> 00:06:32,838
And we said during that time that we would make meaningful changes to our service proposal based on what we heard from you.

59
00:06:33,630 --> 00:06:39,833
And we're here tonight to tell you about the changes that we made, what we heard and what we're doing about it.

60
00:06:40,794 --> 00:06:46,657
Now, a note, the public comment period for this proposal has ended.

61
00:06:47,577 --> 00:06:53,740
The goal here tonight is for us to explain what we heard and how we are changing it in response.

62
00:06:54,861 --> 00:06:57,642
And our goals for the overall project remain the same.

63
00:06:58,043 --> 00:07:02,585
It is still to create a better bus network, a more equitable service for our riders,

64
00:07:02,958 --> 00:07:08,940
and to transform the entire bus system by creating routes that are more frequent and connect to more places.

65
00:07:10,080 --> 00:07:10,601
How do we do that?

66
00:07:10,621 --> 00:07:12,441
Well, we do it by increasing service.

67
00:07:12,921 --> 00:07:18,643
We still plan to increase service by 25% across the network when we are done.

68
00:07:19,604 --> 00:07:26,486
We are challenged by a bus operator hiring shortage, but we have plans to respond to that.

69
00:07:27,726 --> 00:07:32,248
We also plan to provide hundreds of thousands of riders with higher frequency service.

70
00:07:32,723 --> 00:07:42,129
That's a high frequency service we define as a bus stopping at your stop every 15 minutes or better, seven days a week, all day long.

71
00:07:43,470 --> 00:07:48,193
But to make these improvements, we had to make trade-offs and consider changes.

72
00:07:48,573 --> 00:07:59,140
We weren't able to make all the changes that you requested of us, but we ultimately made changes to about two thirds of the routes in the service proposal you will hear about tonight.

73
00:08:00,465 --> 00:08:15,132
So the revised network map that we will present to you now is, I think, a better plan and a more equitable bus system for current and future bus riders that reflects the changing travel needs with more frequent service, more reliable service, and better connection.

74
00:08:16,733 --> 00:08:18,994
And I just wanted to close by saying thank you.

75
00:08:19,254 --> 00:08:22,575
Thank you for being here tonight to help us build a better bus network.

76
00:08:23,276 --> 00:08:25,216
This is our bus system.

77
00:08:25,317 --> 00:08:27,017
It is not the MBTA's bus system.

78
00:08:27,398 --> 00:08:28,398
It is not yours alone.

79
00:08:29,672 --> 00:08:37,476
Everyone here, including me, including all of the MBTA staff here tonight, ride the bus and care about the bus very deeply.

80
00:08:38,516 --> 00:08:40,717
Now back to Doug Johnson, project manager.

81
00:08:43,463 --> 00:08:44,164
Thank you, Justin.

82
00:08:44,184 --> 00:08:46,647
Hi everyone, thank you for joining us tonight.

83
00:08:47,328 --> 00:08:52,234
As Justin mentioned, my name is Doug Johnson and I'm the project manager for bus network redesign.

84
00:08:53,035 --> 00:09:00,985
Tonight's meeting will begin with a brief presentation about bus network redesign, and the changes that have been made to the proposal that we published back in May.

85
00:09:01,946 --> 00:09:20,627
As Justin mentioned, and as you know, back in May we published a draft network map, and we solicited public feedback on it through September, we ultimately received over 20,000 comments on the draft proposal, and we've incorporated that feedback into a revised network map that will present to you tonight.

86
00:09:21,468 --> 00:09:32,536
I will give a general overview of the changes that were made, and then we'll move into breakout rooms where project team members will give presentations about the changes made to specific areas of the network.

87
00:09:33,497 --> 00:09:38,140
In those breakout rooms, you will have the opportunity to ask questions about the changes that were made.

88
00:09:39,121 --> 00:09:44,564
After about 40 minutes, we will return to the main Zoom room for a question and answer session.

89
00:09:45,265 --> 00:09:49,068
At the start of Q&A, we will call on elected officials to make comments first.

90
00:09:50,125 --> 00:10:02,967
If you are not able to stay for the whole meeting, but would like to leave a comment about the revised bus network, you can either post a comment in the chat and we will add it to our records, or you can submit a comment through our online comment form.

91
00:10:02,987 --> 00:10:06,468
A link to that form will be posted in the chat.

92
00:10:10,989 --> 00:10:19,290
Folks may be familiar with the Better Bus Project, but I'll give you a brief description of this effort and how bus network redesign fits into it.

93
00:10:20,227 --> 00:10:37,576
The Better Bus Project is a series of integrated projects across the MBTA that seek to transform and modernize the entire bus system to create more reliable service and a better rider experience.

94
00:10:38,257 --> 00:10:46,161
It includes the bus network redesign, the ongoing effort to modernize our bus maintenance facilities and decarbonize the fleet,

95
00:10:47,261 --> 00:11:09,776
build bus transit priority infrastructure throughout the network, make all bus stops accessible, provide more bus stop amenities like shelters, benches, and lighting, improve the distribution of information to riders about buses, when they will arrive at stops, and about route changes.

96
00:11:11,957 --> 00:11:17,164
as well as change the way that the MBTA collects fares on our system.

97
00:11:18,730 --> 00:11:47,347
Bus network redesign is one piece of that larger effort, and it informs those other efforts by telling us where bus service will go and when, how many operators we'll need, how many buses we'll need, where new bus stops will need to be located, and where we will need to install bus transit priority, things like bus lanes and traffic lights that are specifically for transit vehicles.

98
00:11:50,016 --> 00:12:00,941
So the Bus Network Redesign Project specifically is an effort to reimagine the entire bus network so that it better reflects the needs of the region today.

99
00:12:01,682 --> 00:12:08,705
As folks know, over the last few years and many decades, the region has changed a lot.

100
00:12:09,125 --> 00:12:13,087
People are living in areas that used to be industrial.

101
00:12:13,647 --> 00:12:17,809
There are new job centers that exist now that didn't exist a decade or two.

102
00:12:19,650 --> 00:12:27,029
Earlier, travel patterns have changed both because of COVID and they were changing before COVID.

103
00:12:27,819 --> 00:12:38,483
But the bus network that exists right now doesn't do a good job of addressing that demand and those travel patterns, where people want to go and when they want to go there.

104
00:12:39,363 --> 00:12:43,364
The bus network hasn't really changed very much in about 50 years.

105
00:12:44,144 --> 00:12:50,967
So this effort seeks to redesign it so that it better meets the needs of the region, so that we provide service

106
00:12:52,173 --> 00:12:59,360
to the places that people want to go, when people want to get there, and we provide service that is frequent and reliable.

107
00:13:00,120 --> 00:13:09,509
A good example of that, as you know, right now, the bus network is really focused on providing service on weekday mornings and weekday evenings.

108
00:13:10,210 --> 00:13:15,374
But obviously, people travel all day, every day, not just for

109
00:13:16,415 --> 00:13:18,537
work on weekday mornings and evenings.

110
00:13:19,038 --> 00:13:23,102
People have all different kinds of hours and all different reasons to travel around.

111
00:13:24,283 --> 00:13:27,787
We want to make sure that the bus network meets all of those needs.

112
00:13:31,461 --> 00:13:34,923
Our first goal is to create a more equitable network.

113
00:13:35,503 --> 00:13:58,155
This is about providing more service and more reliable service to the people who are the most dependent on public transit, including low-income populations, households with few or no vehicles, seniors, people with disabilities, and communities of color that do not have equal access to public transit.

114
00:13:59,805 --> 00:14:15,284
We want to create more frequent service in busy neighborhoods, more all day service, service that runs all day, every day, whether it's a weekday or a weekend, and is frequent and reliable regardless of the time of day.

115
00:14:16,322 --> 00:14:25,530
We want to create new connections to more places, including all those non-downtown job centers that exist now that didn't exist a decade or two ago.

116
00:14:26,310 --> 00:14:29,193
We want to make the network simpler and easier to use.

117
00:14:29,853 --> 00:14:40,703
As folks know, right now, sometimes if you get on a bus, it may not go to the same place it usually goes to, depending on the time of day or the day of the week.

118
00:14:41,458 --> 00:14:56,711
We want to make sure that the network is easier to navigate and that routes do consistent things so that you don't have to worry about what time of day it is or what day of the week it is, whether that bus is going to get you home or not.

119
00:14:57,251 --> 00:15:09,402
We want the network to be consistent and reliable enough that folks can show up to a bus stop without having to check the schedule to confirm that that bus is going to come on time or get them to where they need to go.

120
00:15:10,410 --> 00:15:19,638
We also want to implement more transit priority, as I mentioned, and other infrastructure across the network to improve reliability and accessibility.

121
00:15:20,399 --> 00:15:24,522
Many of the bus stops in the current network are not accessible.

122
00:15:25,823 --> 00:15:28,566
They're not compliant with the American with Disabilities Act.

123
00:15:29,286 --> 00:15:35,230
and there are a lot of challenges for folks who are trying to use the bus network at those locations.

124
00:15:35,790 --> 00:15:45,136
These are things that we seek to address through this effort as part of our overall goal of transforming and improving the bus network.

125
00:15:48,318 --> 00:15:58,544
We've developed a revised network proposal using service design principles and the public feedback that we collected over the summer and the fall.

126
00:16:00,110 --> 00:16:20,052
In general, our principles are to prioritize frequency over one-seat rides, create more rapid transit connections and more crosstown routes, focus on all-day service, combine routes to create high-frequency corridors, minimize route variations, and minimize deviations on high-frequency routes.

127
00:16:22,112 --> 00:16:31,040
But service design principles only get us so far, of course, and so does the analysis of quantitative data.

128
00:16:31,421 --> 00:16:42,671
That's the cell phone data that we use to develop the initial network and other metrics like ridership and things that can be quantified or counted.

129
00:16:43,323 --> 00:16:47,487
We know that that alone is not enough to design a bus network.

130
00:16:48,107 --> 00:16:57,256
Public feedback is a really important component and has to be incorporated into the network to ensure that it actually meets people's needs.

131
00:16:58,577 --> 00:17:09,467
We told everyone at the beginning of this process that we would make meaningful changes to the draft network based on the feedback that we received and we have.

132
00:17:11,822 --> 00:17:20,601
The revised bus network would still increase service by 25% across the network versus pre pandemic service.

133
00:17:21,542 --> 00:17:25,043
we would still double the number of high-frequency corridors.

134
00:17:25,583 --> 00:17:31,004
Those are buses coming every 15 minutes or better, all day, seven days a week.

135
00:17:31,684 --> 00:17:38,566
And when we say 15 minutes or better, the goal is for that to be the worst that that service would be.

136
00:17:39,026 --> 00:17:45,368
Some routes would come every four minutes during rush hour, or every six minutes, or every eight minutes.

137
00:17:46,108 --> 00:17:53,055
There are routes in the network today that come that frequently during rush hour, and that we do not intend to change.

138
00:17:53,675 --> 00:18:02,284
But what we want to do is make sure that those really frequent routes are really frequent all day, every day.

139
00:18:03,144 --> 00:18:05,667
The existing key bus routes that we have

140
00:18:07,548 --> 00:18:14,253
Those are our most frequent routes, their frequency varies in during peak periods is when they are most frequent.

141
00:18:15,994 --> 00:18:24,180
Their frequency is more consistent than other routes in the network, but it is still less frequent midday and on weekends.

142
00:18:25,164 --> 00:18:29,809
The map on the left on this slide shows the key bus routes.

143
00:18:30,409 --> 00:18:36,655
The map on the right shows the new high-frequency corridors that would be created by this plan.

144
00:18:37,416 --> 00:18:44,983
You can see that communities like Chelsea, Everett, Medford, Malden, Lynn,

145
00:18:45,904 --> 00:18:59,937
Waltham, South Boston, Roxbury, Dorchester, West Roxbury, Quincy, many of these communities gain high frequency service that they don't have today.

146
00:18:59,957 --> 00:19:10,387
So this is really about creating a network that provides more equitable service across the region and better service for everyone who uses buses.

147
00:19:14,520 --> 00:19:24,408
Based on the feedback that we received over the summer and the fall, we ended up making changes to about two thirds of the routes in the proposal.

148
00:19:24,929 --> 00:19:28,112
We changed 85 of 133 routes.

149
00:19:29,012 --> 00:19:40,842
The changes that we made range from things like making small changes to routes to making complete changes to routes, including

150
00:19:42,323 --> 00:19:49,609
taking routes that exist today and putting them back in the proposal as they exist today or pre-pandemic.

151
00:19:50,370 --> 00:19:58,737
So the types of changes really range from those small changes, depending on the feedback, to wholesale changes to routes.

152
00:19:59,037 --> 00:20:01,079
And I'll talk more about those in the next few slides.

153
00:20:01,299 --> 00:20:10,787
And then the facilitators and breakout rooms will walk through each route in the respective area that that breakout room is associated with and talk about those changes.

154
00:20:12,300 --> 00:20:14,562
There were five main reasons why we made changes.

155
00:20:15,243 --> 00:20:19,306
The first was to respond to public feedback that we received on the draft map.

156
00:20:20,227 --> 00:20:28,095
The second was to improve access to hospitals, senior centers, grocery stores, shopping malls, and other destinations.

157
00:20:29,057 --> 00:20:44,010
The third was to reduce the walk distances, specifically for seniors, riders with disabilities, and riders with mobility challenges, and especially in locations with really challenging terrain or pedestrian conditions.

158
00:20:44,991 --> 00:20:55,540
I mentioned the service design principles earlier, where we said we wanted to focus on more frequent service and combining services so that they'd be more frequent.

159
00:20:56,488 --> 00:21:08,933
The trade off with doing that is that there are situations in which we would be asking folks to walk further to get to a bus stop than they have to walk today in order to have a much better service.

160
00:21:09,633 --> 00:21:15,536
We heard a lot of feedback about that specifically from folks on the draft map.

161
00:21:16,076 --> 00:21:26,625
And we looked at those situations where folks said that increased walking distance would be a hardship and a barrier to accessing the service for them.

162
00:21:27,326 --> 00:21:40,557
So we took that feedback to heart and we adjusted many of our routes to reduce those walking distances in situations where folks told us it would be too much of a hardship or barrier to accessing the service.

163
00:21:42,062 --> 00:21:47,246
The fourth reason was to preserve some existing one seat rides to certain destinations.

164
00:21:49,108 --> 00:21:58,596
In the draft network, one of the things that we were doing was creating a network of really high frequency routes.

165
00:21:59,527 --> 00:22:13,376
But a trade-off with that is that in some cases, a route that you have today, that's a one-seat ride, meaning you get on a bus, it takes you from point A to point B without you having to transfer or get on a different bus.

166
00:22:13,877 --> 00:22:14,777
That's a one-seat ride.

167
00:22:15,338 --> 00:22:23,183
In the draft network that we had proposed, there were some situations where existing one-seat rides would be broken up into a two-seat ride.

168
00:22:23,463 --> 00:22:25,865
So you would have to transfer from one service to another.

169
00:22:26,914 --> 00:22:36,946
If those two routes are very frequent and very reliable, then it won't impact your travel time very much to have to make that transfer.

170
00:22:37,915 --> 00:22:57,664
But we know that there are locations where transferring from one service to another can be really challenging or can be a big increase in the amount of time that you're spending getting from point A to point B. So we've reviewed all the feedback that we received a lot of feedback about that specifically.

171
00:22:58,124 --> 00:23:02,486
And we took a really close look at that and ultimately decided that in some situations,

172
00:23:03,439 --> 00:23:07,244
It was better to put a route, a one seat ride back into the network.

173
00:23:07,844 --> 00:23:13,911
And I think a good example of that is the route 39 from Jamaica Plain to Copley and Back Bay.

174
00:23:14,512 --> 00:23:18,256
We had proposed the 39 going from Jamaica Plain into Cambridge.

175
00:23:18,977 --> 00:23:25,160
but we heard a lot of feedback on it and decided ultimately to revert it back to what it does today.

176
00:23:25,421 --> 00:23:28,262
So the 39 would continue to do what it does today.

177
00:23:28,842 --> 00:23:46,832
If folks want to travel to Cambridge from JP, there are other options in this new network for them to transfer from the 39 to our new 47 or other routes, but that's an example where we put back what exists in the network today because of the feedback that we got.

178
00:23:48,067 --> 00:23:55,572
And then the fifth reason for changes were to balance our resources and stay within the limits that bound us.

179
00:23:56,453 --> 00:24:01,316
There are a maximum number of buses that we can run at any given time.

180
00:24:02,117 --> 00:24:07,721
Without increasing the size of the fleet, we can't go beyond that current limit.

181
00:24:08,851 --> 00:24:17,624
There's also a maximum amount of service hours revenue vehicle hours that we can run and stay within our budget.

182
00:24:18,285 --> 00:24:22,751
So that is a hard limit as well, and we had to stay within that it's still a 25% increase over the

183
00:24:25,335 --> 00:24:29,999
pre-pandemic amount of service that we were providing, and I want to be clear on that.

184
00:24:30,019 --> 00:24:37,726
We will be providing 25% more service versus what we were providing pre-pandemic, not today.

185
00:24:38,426 --> 00:24:45,973
Obviously, as folks know, there is less service provided today because of operator shortage challenges that we are facing right now.

186
00:24:47,602 --> 00:24:50,224
So those were limits that we had to stay within.

187
00:24:51,125 --> 00:25:07,376
So we were not able to make every single change that was requested of us, but we did our best to respond to as much of the public feedback as we possibly could and really make this a much better network based on the feedback that we received.

188
00:25:09,337 --> 00:25:12,720
There are five main categories for types of changes that were made.

189
00:25:13,380 --> 00:25:15,222
The first was restoring

190
00:25:16,652 --> 00:25:23,015
existing route either to what it does today either in whole or in part.

191
00:25:23,775 --> 00:25:26,056
I'll give you a few examples on this list.

192
00:25:27,357 --> 00:25:34,180
The 39 I already mentioned will continue to do what it does today going from Jamaica Plain to Copley and Back Bay.

193
00:25:35,460 --> 00:25:43,064
We put part of the 47 back but then also extended the 47 in different ways so it looks slightly different than it does today.

194
00:25:44,167 --> 00:25:47,910
The 55 will continue to do what it does today.

195
00:25:48,190 --> 00:25:59,779
We have proposed the 55 going to Kendall rather than going from Fenway to Copley, but we heard a lot of feedback on it, and the 55 will continue to do what it does today.

196
00:26:00,479 --> 00:26:07,165
I want to be clear that it will not go to Park Street as it did in the past, but it will continue to do what it does today.

197
00:26:09,161 --> 00:26:15,228
The 87 and the 89 are routes that we made changes to in response to the feedback that we received.

198
00:26:16,269 --> 00:26:22,236
The 201, the 202 are back to in this network doing what they do today.

199
00:26:22,256 --> 00:26:26,461
So we rescinded the alternate proposal that we have for those routes.

200
00:26:28,023 --> 00:26:32,625
The 354 was not included in the initial proposal that we released in May.

201
00:26:33,105 --> 00:26:41,730
That is back in this new network providing express service from Burlington and Woburn down 93 to Medford Square and into downtown.

202
00:26:42,411 --> 00:26:46,913
And then the 505 we had proposed a modification to its routing.

203
00:26:48,914 --> 00:26:53,617
We reverted it back to the routing that it has today due to feedback from

204
00:26:55,958 --> 00:26:56,579
City of Needham.

205
00:26:57,499 --> 00:26:58,600
So, excuse me, Newton.

206
00:27:00,642 --> 00:27:02,083
That's the first category of changes.

207
00:27:03,124 --> 00:27:12,352
The second was rerouting routes, making small changes to routes to better connect to medical facilities, senior housing, and other destinations.

208
00:27:12,713 --> 00:27:16,076
This is a major theme that we heard in the public feedback.

209
00:27:17,053 --> 00:27:19,774
routes like the T8 and the T12.

210
00:27:20,074 --> 00:27:26,156
And I wanna note here that the letter T in front of a number means that that will be a high frequency route.

211
00:27:26,676 --> 00:27:30,998
It will come every 15 minutes or better all day from 5 a.m.

212
00:27:31,118 --> 00:27:31,758
to 1 a.m.

213
00:27:32,138 --> 00:27:33,018
seven days a week.

214
00:27:33,678 --> 00:27:37,940
In some cases, those routes are even more frequent during rush hours.

215
00:27:39,260 --> 00:27:44,302
So the T8 and the T12, we modified to better connect to Boston Medical Center.

216
00:27:45,313 --> 00:27:49,396
the 11 will continue to serve Tufts Medical Center directly.

217
00:27:50,117 --> 00:27:55,861
In the draft proposal, we had proposed the 11 stopping at the Broadway red line station.

218
00:27:56,581 --> 00:28:02,026
But based on feedback that we got from folks, we decided to extend the 11 to Tufts Medical Center.

219
00:28:02,726 --> 00:28:04,467
It won't do exactly what it does today.

220
00:28:04,728 --> 00:28:11,873
It won't loop through downtown and down A street, but it will go from South Boston to Tufts Medical Center and back directly.

221
00:28:14,945 --> 00:28:20,308
Other routes like the T-104, that will do something very different than what it does today.

222
00:28:20,488 --> 00:28:24,930
It will still start at Malden Center, but it will go to East Boston through Everett and Chelsea.

223
00:28:25,650 --> 00:28:33,474
We modified that proposal to better serve the grocery store in Chelsea, the Market Basket, and to connect to the airport Blue Line station.

224
00:28:34,254 --> 00:28:43,218
You can see the other routes on this list where there were other small route modifications made to that May proposal in response to this feedback that we got.

225
00:28:44,541 --> 00:28:51,524
The third category was adding routes to the proposal that were not in the proposal for May.

226
00:28:51,564 --> 00:28:57,767
The 113 is a brand new route that we've added that goes from Chelsea to Assembly Row by way of Everett Square.

227
00:28:58,868 --> 00:29:03,750
That was a change we made in relation to some other changes, the 90 in Somerville.

228
00:29:05,653 --> 00:29:13,137
The 47, I mentioned, is a route we've reintroduced, it will continue to do partly what it does today, but not the entirety of what it does today.

229
00:29:13,818 --> 00:29:19,962
If you join the breakout room that covers Cambridge, and the surrounding municipalities you'll hear more about that route.

230
00:29:21,925 --> 00:29:26,387
The fourth category of changes was frequency and span adjustments.

231
00:29:26,647 --> 00:29:33,368
So that's how often a bus comes and then span is the time, the hours of the day that it runs.

232
00:29:34,009 --> 00:29:38,590
So those are routes where we adjusted the frequency and span but we didn't adjust the route.

233
00:29:39,210 --> 00:29:46,252
And a good example of that is the 504, where we've added some midday service to it, and the SL2.

234
00:29:46,913 --> 00:29:59,137
We had proposed making the SL2 peak period only, basically rush hour only on weekdays, but the SL2 will now be a high frequency route seven days a week.

235
00:30:00,397 --> 00:30:06,379
And then the last category were routes that were included in the May proposal that are not in a revised network.

236
00:30:07,670 --> 00:30:09,452
An example of this is the Route 20.

237
00:30:10,252 --> 00:30:15,237
We had proposed the Route 20 to do what the 201 and 202 do to some extent.

238
00:30:19,432 --> 00:30:25,513
Because we have restored the 201 and the 202, we have rescinded this proposal for the Route 20.

239
00:30:26,213 --> 00:30:29,094
So there were a handful of other routes where that was the case.

240
00:30:29,974 --> 00:30:31,695
The 350 is an example.

241
00:30:32,455 --> 00:30:47,378
We have reintroduced to some extent the Route 80, but now the 80 in this new network will do what we have proposed for the 350, as well as providing a connection between Arlington Center and Somerville that is not covered by the Green Line extension.

242
00:30:48,423 --> 00:30:55,865
So there were a small number of routes that had been in the proposal that were removed because of other changes that we made in the network.

243
00:30:58,005 --> 00:30:59,166
So those are the main categories.

244
00:30:59,606 --> 00:31:08,048
You will hear the actual details of these changes and see maps in the breakout rooms that we'll move to shortly.

245
00:31:10,763 --> 00:31:13,285
The revised bus network is now publicly available.

246
00:31:14,006 --> 00:31:19,210
You can go to the project website, which is mbta.com slash BNRD.

247
00:31:20,350 --> 00:31:32,340
On the project website, there is a list of all the changes made to the May 2022 proposal, both an interactive map and a static PDF map that you can look at.

248
00:31:33,120 --> 00:31:38,645
And there's a link to the online comment form where folks can leave comments about the revised bus network.

249
00:31:39,480 --> 00:31:47,918
All of your comments will be shared with the Bus Transformation Office, which is tasked with implementation of the new network.

250
00:31:49,069 --> 00:31:53,371
We are also conducting an equity analysis of the revised bus network.

251
00:31:53,891 --> 00:31:57,753
That is underway right now and will be completed by December.

252
00:31:58,354 --> 00:32:09,899
That is required of us by the FTA, or it's required of all transit agencies by the FTA when an agency wants to make changes that surpass a certain threshold.

253
00:32:10,620 --> 00:32:17,083
Because we are redesigning the entire network, we surpass that threshold and we are required to conduct this equity analysis.

254
00:32:17,841 --> 00:32:25,015
There will be a public meeting for that, the results of that equity analysis to present it to the public this winter.

255
00:32:28,765 --> 00:32:33,887
The changes that we are proposing to the bus network are not going to happen overnight.

256
00:32:34,787 --> 00:32:40,269
We anticipate that it will take a total of five years to implement this new network.

257
00:32:41,089 --> 00:32:49,272
It will be done in phases as our bus operator headcount allows, beginning in the summer of 2023.

258
00:32:51,052 --> 00:32:58,475
Changes will likely be made with the summer service changes each year between 2023 and 2027.

259
00:32:59,695 --> 00:33:08,478
There are also a number of capital projects or construction projects that will need to take place in order to make this new network possible.

260
00:33:09,178 --> 00:33:13,240
We are in the process of identifying new stop locations

261
00:33:14,444 --> 00:33:33,850
where existing stops that are not accessible will need to either be upgraded or relocated so that they can be accessible, as well as where transit priority infrastructure will need to be implemented in order to allow the service to maintain the reliability that we want it to have.

262
00:33:34,650 --> 00:33:41,993
Those are things, as I mentioned, like bus lanes and dedicated traffic signals specifically for buses.

263
00:33:42,393 --> 00:33:51,717
If you're familiar with the Green Line, you know that the Green Line, the B branch, C branch, D and E, when they're

264
00:33:53,180 --> 00:33:57,822
in the roadway or on the surface, there are dedicated signals for them at intersections.

265
00:33:58,303 --> 00:34:12,830
So that is something that we will be implementing across the network for buses in places where we want to make bus service more reliable or have it have dedicated roadway space or exclusive time in a signal phase.

266
00:34:14,291 --> 00:34:19,454
The work to identify all of those projects and those locations is underway right now.

267
00:34:20,372 --> 00:34:36,134
And we are working on a plan to both address the operator shortage that we and many transit agencies across the country are experiencing, as well as the implications for that with the implementation phasing that we are planning right now.

268
00:34:39,114 --> 00:34:42,257
That concludes this overview presentation.

269
00:34:43,278 --> 00:34:55,109
Before we move to breakout rooms, I just want to say, or leave these resources here for a moment so that folks have the project website, you can see it's the first address there, mbta.com slash BNRD.

270
00:34:56,674 --> 00:35:09,083
The online feedback form, you can find it on the project website or you can use the link mbta.com slash BNRD feedback that will take you directly to that online feedback form.

271
00:35:09,984 --> 00:35:16,849
And you can learn more about the Bettered Bus project at that project website, mbta.com slash Bettered Bus.

272
00:35:17,489 --> 00:35:22,473
Of course, you can continue to email the MBTA as well, your questions and comments.

273
00:35:23,483 --> 00:35:31,970
I'll now turn it back over to Regan Cecchio, who will go over how the breakout rooms will work.

274
00:35:35,273 --> 00:35:35,794
Thanks, Doug.

275
00:35:36,714 --> 00:35:45,362
So, as he mentioned, we're going to be having some presentations in breakout rooms by area to answer your questions about the revised map.

276
00:35:46,343 --> 00:35:47,584
Can you go to the next slide, Doug?

277
00:35:50,026 --> 00:35:50,246
So,

278
00:35:52,962 --> 00:35:55,985
On screen, and I will read them out for the benefit of the interpreters.

279
00:35:56,065 --> 00:36:01,469
You can see there are breakout rooms cross reference by municipality.

280
